ps (1986\u20132010)|Vancouver Whitecaps]]||[[USL First Division|First Division]]||7||1||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||9||1\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Scotland\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Scottish Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]]\n\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Scottish First Division|2008\u201309]]||[[Dundee F.C.]]||[[Scottish First Division|First Division]]||26||1||1||0||0||0||27||1\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Canada\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Canadian Championship|Voyageurs Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2009 United Soccer Leagues|2009]]||rowspan=\"2\"|Vancouver Whitecaps||First Division|| || || || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014|| ||\n|-\n|[[USSF Division 2 Professional League|2010]]||USSF Division 2|| || || || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014|| ||\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Norway\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Norwegian Football Cup|Norwegian Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2010 Norwegian Premier League|2010]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[FK Haugesund|Haugesund]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Norwegian Premier League|Tippeligaen]]||28||1||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||32||1\n|-\n|[[2011 Norwegian Premier League|2011]]||25||1||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||28||1\n|-\n|[[2012 Norwegian Premier League|2012]]||1||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0\n|-\n|[[2012 Norwegian First Division|2012]]||rowspan=\"1\"|[[Bryne FK|Bryne]]||rowspan=\"1\"|[[Adeccoligaen]]||8||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||8||0\n|-\n!rowspan=5| Country !!colspan=2| Canada\n!71||1||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||73||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Sweden\n!45||1|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||45||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Norway\n!109||11||9||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||118||12\n|-\n!colspan=2|United States\n!4||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Scotland\n!26||1||1||0||0||0||27||1\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Career total\n!255||14||12||1||0||0||267||15\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110605070210/http://www.canadasoccer.com/players/profile.asp?playerid=24&gender=male Player profile] \u2013 CanadaSoccer\n*{{NFT player|pid=1272}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091118161158/http://www.whitecapsfc.com/men/roster/players/chris_pozniak.aspx Player profile] \u2013 Vancouover Whitecaps\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Canada squads\n| bg = red\n| fg = white\n|list1=\n{{Canada Squad 2002 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Canada Squad 2003 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Canada Squad 2005 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Canada Squad 2007 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Canada Squad 2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n}}\n{{Toronto FC II squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pozniak, Chris}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Krak\u00f3w]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Canada]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Canadian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Canada men's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:2002 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:2003 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:2005 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:2007 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Toronto Lynx players]]\n[[Category:\u00d6rebro SK players]]\n[[Category:FK Haugesund players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Toronto FC players]]\n[[Category:Chivas USA players]]\n[[Category:Vancouver Whitecaps (1986\u20132010) players]]\n[[Category:Dundee F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bryne FK players]]\n[[Category:Allsvenskan players]]\n[[Category:1. divisjon players]]\n[[Category:Eliteserien players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:USL First Division players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Norway]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canada men's youth international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Canada men's under-23 international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Canadian soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCoaching career:Typo fixing, replaced: teams new \u2192 team's new", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Pozniak"}
{"title_page": "Richard Rodney Bennett", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix    = [[Sir]]\n| name                = Richard Rodney Bennett\n| honorific_suffix    = {{postnom|country=GBR|size=100|CBE}}\n| image               = Sir-Richard-Rodney-Bennett.jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| birth_name          = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1936|03|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Broadstairs|Broadstairs, Kent]], England\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2012|12|24|1936|03|29|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[New York City]], US\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Classical music]]|[[film music]]|[[jazz]]}}\n| occupation          = [[Composer]]\n| instrument          = [[Piano]]\n| years_active        = 1954\u20132012\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}}  -->\n\n| module              = \n| module2             = \n| module3             = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Richard Rodney Bennett''' {{postnom|country=GBR|CBE}} (29 March 1936{{spaced ndash}}24 December 2012) was an English [[composer]] of film, TV and [[classical music|concert music]], and also a jazz pianist. He was based in [[New York City]] from 1979 until his death there in 2012.<ref name=\"Woolfe\">Zachary Woolfe [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/31/arts/music/richard-rodney-bennett-british-composer-dies-at-76.html?_r=0 \"Richard Rodney Bennett, British Composer, Dies at 76\",] ''New York Times'', 30 December 2012</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\nBennett was born at [[Broadstairs]], [[Kent]], but was raised in Devon during [[World War II]].<ref name=\"Woolfe\"/> His mother, Joan Esther, n\u00e9e Spink (1901\u20131983)<ref>{{Citation|last=Venn|first=Edward|title=Bennett, Sir Richard Rodney (1936\u20132012), composer|date=2016-01-07|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-105846|work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/105846|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> was a pianist who had trained with [[Gustav Holst]] and sang in the first professional performance of ''[[The Planets]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/Writers-and-Production-Artists-Ba-Bo/Bennett-Sir-Richard-Rodney.html |title=Sir Richard Rodney Bennett \u2013 Writer \u2013 Films as Composer:, Publications |publisher=Filmreference.com |accessdate=2014-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/38/Richard-Rodney-Bennett.html |title=Richard Rodney Bennett Biography (1936\u2013) |publisher=Filmreference.com |date=1936-03-29 |accessdate=2014-05-15}}</ref> His father, Rodney Bennett, (1890\u20131948) was a children's book author, poet and lyricist, who worked with [[Roger Quilter]] on his theatre works and provided new words for some of the numbers in the ''[[Arnold Book of Old Songs]]''.\n\nBennett was a pupil at [[Leighton Park School]].<ref name=\"Sweeting\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/dec/26/sir-richard-rodney-bennett | title=Sir Richard Rodney Bennett obituary | work=The Guardian | author=[[Adam Sweeting]] | date=2012-12-26 | accessdate=2015-07-24}}</ref> He later studied at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] with [[Howard Ferguson (composer)|Howard Ferguson]], [[Lennox Berkeley]] and [[Cornelius Cardew]]. Ferguson regarded him as extraordinarily brilliant, having perhaps the greatest talent of any British composer in his generation, though lacking in a personal style. During this time, Bennett attended some of the [[Darmstadt]] summer courses in 1955, where he was exposed to [[serialism]]. He later spent two years in [[Paris]] as a student of the prominent serialist [[Pierre Boulez]] between 1957 and 1959.<ref>Robert Ponsonby [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/sir-richard-rodney-bennett-composer-whose-work-encompassed-serialism-tonality-and-popular-music-8431646.html \"Sir Richard Rodney Bennett: Composer whose work encompassed serialism, tonality and popular music\",] ''The Independent'', 26 December 2012</ref> He always used both his first names after finding another Richard Bennett active in music.\n\nBennett taught at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] between 1963 and 1965, at the [[Peabody Institute]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]], United States from 1970 to 1971, and was later International [[Chair]] of Composition at the Royal Academy of Music between 1994 and the year 2000. He was appointed a Commander of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in 1977, and was [[Knight Bachelor|knight]]ed in 1998.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/for_christmas/_new_year/new_year_honours/43509.stm | work=BBC News | title=Life Peers to Order of the Companion of Honour | date=31 December 1997}}</ref>\n\nBennett produced over 200 works for the concert hall, and 50 scores for film and television. He was also a writer and performer of [[jazz]] songs for 50 years. Immersed in the techniques of the European [[avant-garde]] via his contact with Boulez, Bennett subsequently developed his own dramato-abstract style. In his later years, he adopted an increasingly tonal idiom.\n\nBennett regularly performed as a jazz pianist, with such singers as [[Cleo Laine]], [[Marion Montgomery]] (until her death in 2002), [[Mary Cleere Haran]] (until her death in 2011), and more recently with [[Claire Martin (singer)|Claire Martin]],<ref name=\"Sweeting\"/> performing the [[Great American Songbook]]. Bennett and Martin performed at such venues as The Oak Room at the [[Algonquin Hotel]] in New York, and [[The Pheasantry]] and [[Ronnie Scott's Jazz Club]] in London.\n\nIn later years, in addition to his musical activities, Bennett became known as an artist working in the medium of collage.<ref name=\"Wroe\">{{cite web|author=Nicholas Wroe |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/jul/22/richard-rodney-bennett-life-music-film |title=A life in music: Richard Rodney Bennett &#124; Music |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=2014-05-15}}</ref> He exhibited these collages several times in England, including at the [http://www.holtfestival.org/ Holt Festival, Norfolk]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://holtfestival.org/2011/fine_art.html |title=Holt Festival 2011 &#124; Fine Art |publisher=Holtfestival.org |accessdate=2014-05-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922184428/http://holtfestival.org/2011/fine_art.html |archivedate=22 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> in 2011, and at the Swaledale Festival, Yorkshire, in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swaledale-festival.org.uk/exhib |title=music, poetry, visual arts, walks, exhibitions, workshops |publisher=Swaledale Festival |accessdate=2014-05-15}}</ref> The first ever exhibition of his collages was in London in 2010, at the South Kensington and Chelsea Mental Health Centre, curated by the Nightingale Project, a charity that takes music and art into hospitals. Bennett was a patron of this charity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nightingaleproject.org |title=The Nightingale Project |publisher=The Nightingale Project |accessdate=2014-05-15}}</ref> Bennett is honoured with four photographic portraits in the collection of the [[National Portrait Gallery, London]].\n\nAnthony Meredith's biography of Bennett was published in November 2010.<ref>{{cite book | title=Richard Rodney Bennett: The Complete Musician | last=Meredith | first=Anthony |author2=Harris, Paul | isbn=978-1-84938-545-9 | publisher=Omnibus | year=2010 | url=http://www.omnibuspress.com/Product.aspx?ProductId=710841}}</ref> Bennett is survived by his sister Meg (born 1930), the poet [[M. R. Peacocke]], with whom he collaborated on a number of vocal works.\n\nBennett's cremated remains are buried at [[Green-wood Cemetery]], [[Brooklyn]].<ref>[https://www.green-wood.com/2013/sir-richard-rodney-bennett-dead-at-76/ Green-Wood]</ref>\n\n==Music==\nDespite his early studies in [[Modernism (music)|modernist]] techniques, Bennett's tastes were catholic. He wrote in a wide range of styles, including [[jazz]], for which he had a particular fondness. Early on, he began to write music for feature films. He said that it was as if the different styles of music that he was writing went on 'in different rooms, albeit in the same house'.<ref name=\"Wroe\"/> Later in his career the different aspects all became equally celebrated&nbsp;\u2013 for example in his 75th birthday year (2011), there were numerous concerts featuring all the different strands of his work. At the BBC Proms for example his ''Murder on the Orient Express Suite'' was performed in a concert of film music, and in the same season his ''Dream Dancing'' and ''[[Jazz Calendar]]'' were also featured. Also at the [[Wigmore Hall]], London, on 23 March 2011 (a few days before Bennett's 75th birthday), a double concert took place in which his [[Claude Debussy|Debussy]]-inspired piece ''Sonata After Syrinx'' was performed in the first concert, and in the Late Night Jazz Event which followed, Bennett and Claire Martin performed his arrangements of the Great American Songbook (Cole Porter, George Gershwin, Rodgers and Hart and so on). See also [https://www.theguardian.com/music/tomserviceblog/2012/jul/02/richard-rodney-bennett-contemporary-music-guide Tom Service's appreciation of Bennett's music] published in The Guardian in July 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/tomserviceblog/2012/jul/02/richard-rodney-bennett-contemporary-music-guide | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Tom | last=Service | title=A guide to Richard Rodney Bennett's music | date=2 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Film and television scores==\nHe wrote music for films and television; among his scores were the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' story ''[[The Aztecs (Doctor Who)|The Aztecs]]'' (1964) for television, and the feature films ''[[Billion Dollar Brain]]'' (1967), ''[[Lady Caroline Lamb (film)|Lady Caroline Lamb]]'' (1972) and ''[[Equus (film)|Equus]]'' (1977). His scores for ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]]'' (1967), ''[[Nicholas and Alexandra]]'' (1971), and ''[[Murder on the Orient Express (1974 film)|Murder on the Orient Express]]'' (1974), each earned him [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominations, with ''Murder on the Orient Express'' gaining a [[BAFTA]] award. Later works include ''[[Enchanted April (1992 film)|Enchanted April]]'' (1992), ''[[Four Weddings and a Funeral]]'' (1994), and ''[[The Tale of Sweeney Todd]]'' (1998). He was also a prolific composer of orchestral works, piano solos, choral works and operas. Despite this eclecticism, Bennett's music rarely involved stylistic crossover.\n\n==Selected works==\n\n===Instrumental works===\n*''Sonata'' for piano (1954, first published work)\n*''Impromptus'' (for guitar) (1968)\n*''Concerto for alto saxophone''\n*''Scena II'' (for solo cello; commissioned by the Music Department of the University College of North Wales, Bangor, with funds from Welsh Arts Council, first performed by Judith Mitchell 25 April 1974\n*''Concerto for Stan Getz'' (tenor saxophone, timpani & strings)\n*''Dream Sequence'' for cello and piano&nbsp;\u2013 first performed in December 1994 at the [[Wigmore Hall]], London by [[Julian Lloyd Webber]] and [[John Lenehan]]\n*''Elegy for Davis''\n*''Harpsichord Concerto'' (1980). Premiere conducted by [[Leonard Slatkin]]. St. Louis Symphony Orchestra. Richard Rodney Bennett, harpsichord.  \n*''Fanfare'' for brass quintet (2012)\n*''Farnham Festival Overture'' (1964) for orchestra\n*''The Four Seasons'' (1991) for Symphonic Wind Ensemble\n*''A Little Suite'', based on selections from Rodney Bennett's song cycles ''The Insect World'' and ''The Aviary''.\n*''Morning Music'' for wind band\n* ''Music for Strings''\n*''Party Piece'' for orchestra\n*''Reflections on a Sixteenth Century Tune'' for string orchestra or double wind quintet (1999)\n*''Sonata for solo guitar'' (1983)\n*''Sonatina'' for solo clarinet\n*''Summer Music'' for flute and piano\n*''Symphony No. 1'' (1965)\n*''Symphony No. 2'' (1968). Commissioned by the [[New York Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n*''Symphony No. 3'' (1987)\n*''Marimba Concerto'' (1988)\n*''Percussion Concerto'' (1990). Commissioned by and first performed at [[St Magnus Festival]], Orkney, soloist Dame [[Evelyn Glennie]], 1990\n*''Trumpet Concerto'' for trumpet and wind orchestra\n*''Partridge Pie'' based on The Twelve Days of Christmas\n*''After Syrinx I'' for oboe and piano\n*''Lilliburlero'' ''Variations for 2 pianos'' (2008) commissioned by the Dranoff 2 Piano Foundation in Miami\n\n===Operas===\n*''[[The Ledge (opera)|The Ledge]]'' (libretto by Adrian Mitchell) \u2013 1961\n*''[[The Midnight Thief]]'' (libretto by [[Ian Serraillier]])&nbsp;\u2013 1964\n*''[[The Mines of Sulphur]]'' (libretto by [[Beverley Cross]]) \u2013 1965\n*''[[A Penny for a Song]]'' \u2013 1967\n*''[[All the King's Men (opera)|All the King's Men]]'' (libretto by Beverley Cross) \u2013 1968\n*''[[Victory (opera)|Victory]]'' (libretto by Beverley Cross) \u2013 1970\n\n===Ballet===\n*''[[Jazz Calendar]]'' \u2013 1968\n*''[[Isadora (ballet)|Isadora]]'' \u2013 1981\n\n===Choral and vocal works===\n* A Good-Night \u2013 1999\n*''Missa Brevis'' \u2013 1990\n*''Sea Change'' \u2013 1983\n*''Spells'', written for soprano [[Jane Manning]]\n*''Five Carols: There is No Rose, Out of Your Sleep, That Younge Child, Sweet was the Song, Susanni'' Written for St Matthew's Church Northampton - 1967\n*''On Christmas Day to My Heart'', written in 1998 for the [[Nine Lessons and Carols|Festival of Nine Lessons and Carols]] at [[King's College Chapel, Cambridge]] in 1999.\n*''The Garden \u2013 A Serenade to Glimmerglass'', commissioned by Nicholas Russell for [[Glimmerglass Opera]] in honour of Stewart Robertson for its Young American Artists Program \u2013 2006\n* The Birds Lament\n* \"Tom o' Bedlam's Song\" (voice and cello){{snd}}1961 <ref>{{Allmusic |class=composition |id=tom-obedlams-song-for-voice-cello-mc0002687471 |label=Richard Rodney Bennett: Tom O'Bedlam's Song, for voice & cello |accessdate=7 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Albums===\nSolo:\n*2007 \"Richard Rodney Bennett: Words And Music\" (Chandos)\n*2002 Take Love Easy (Audiophile)\n*1995 A Different Side of Sondheim (DRG)\n*1994 Harold Arlen's Songs (Audiophile)\n*1992 \"I Never Went Away\" (Delos)\nwith [[Marion Montgomery]]\n*1977 ''Surprise Surprise''\n*1978 ''Town and Country''\n*1984 ''[[Puttin' On the Ritz]]''\nwith Carol Sloane (singer)\n*1988 ''[[Lush Life (Richard Rodney Bennett album)|Lush Life]]''\n*1989 ''Love You Madly'' (Contemporary)\nwith Chris Connor (singer)\n*1991 ''Classic'' (Contemporary)\n*1991 ''New Again'' (Contemporary)\n\nwith Mary Cleere Haran (singer)\n*1995 ''This Funny World: Mary Cleere Haran Sings Lyrics By Hart'' (Var\u00e8se Sarabande)\n*1998 ''Pennies From Heaven: Movie Songs From The Depression Era'' (Angel Records) \n*1999 ''The Memory Of All That: Gershwin On Broadway and In Hollywood'' (2011 reissue)\n*2002 ''Crazy Rhythm: Manhattan in the 20s'' (Var\u00e8se Sarabande)\nwith [[Claire Martin (singer)|Claire Martin]]\n*2005 ''[[When Lights Are Low (Claire Martin and Richard Rodney Bennett album)|When Lights Are Low]]''\n*2010 ''[[Witchcraft (Claire Martin and Richard Rodney Bennett album)|Witchcraft]]''\n*2013 ''Say It Isn't So''\nOpera\n*2005 ''The Mines of Sulphur'' (Chandos)\nOrchestral\n*1968 Symphony No. 1 (with works by Bax and Berkeley) \u2013 [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]], [[Igor Buketoff]] (RCA)\n*1972 ''Jazz Calendar'' / Piano Concerto \u2013 [[Stephen Bishop-Kovacevich]], [[London Symphony Orchestra]], [[Alexander Gibson (conductor)|Alexander Gibson]] (Philips)\n*1979 ''Spells'' / ''Aubade'' \u2013 [[Jane Manning]], [[Philharmonia Orchestra]], [[David Willcocks]], [[David Atherton]] (Argo)\n*1995 ''Partita'' / ''Four Jazz Songs'' / ''Enchanted April Suite'' \u2013 [[Britten Sinfonia]], [[Nicholas Cleobury]], the composer, [[Neil Richardson (composer)|Neil Richardson]] (BBC)\n*1996 ''Diversions'' / Symphony No. 3 / Concerto for Violin and Orchestra \u2013 [[Monte Carlo Philharmonic Orchestra]], [[James DePreist]] (Koch)\n*2017 ''Bennett: Orchestral Works , Vol 1 (Celebration; Marimba Concerto; Symphony No. 3; Summer Music; Sinfonietta)'' - BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra, John Wilson (Chandos)\n*2018 ''Bennett: Orchestral Works , Vol 2 (Concerto for Stan Getz; Symphony No. 2; Serenade; Partita)'' - BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra, John Wilson (Chandos)\n*2019 ''Bennett: Orchestral Works, Vol 3 (Symphony No. 1; A History of the Dansant; Reflections on a 16th Century Tune; Zodiac)'' - BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra, John Wilson (Chandon)\nChoral\n*2013 ''Letters to Lindbergh'' (Signum UK)\n*2013 ''Sea Change: Choral Music of Richard Rodney Bennett'' \u2013 The [[Cambridge Singers]], the composer and [[John Rutter]] (Collegium Records)\n\n==Selected TV and filmography==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n* ''[[Pickup Alley]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Face in the Night]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[The Safecracker]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[Indiscreet (1958 film)|Indiscreet]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[The Man Inside (1958 film)|The Man Inside]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[The Man Who Could Cheat Death]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[The Angry Hills (film)|The Angry Hills]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[Blind Date (1959 film)|Chance Meeting]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[The Devil's Disciple (1959 film)|The Devil's Disciple]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[The Mark (1961 film)|The Mark]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[Only Two Can Play]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[Satan Never Sleeps]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[The Wrong Arm of the Law]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[Heavens Above!]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[Billy Liar (film)|Billy Liar]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[Hamlet at Elsinore]]'' (1964) (TV)\n* ''[[One Way Pendulum (film)|One Way Pendulum]]'' (1964)\n* ''[[The Wednesday Play]]'' (1964\u20131967) (TV, 3 episodes)\n* ''[[The Nanny (1965 film)|The Nanny]]'' (1965)\n* ''[[The Witches (1966 film)|The Witches]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]]'' (1967) ([[40th Academy Awards|nominated for Academy Award]] for Best Original Score)\n* ''[[Billion Dollar Brain]]'' (1967)\n* ''[[Secret Ceremony]]'' (1968)\n* ''[[The Buttercup Chain]]'' (1970)\n* ''[[Figures in a Landscape (film)|Figures in a Landscape]]'' (1970)\n{{col-3}}\n* ''[[Nicholas and Alexandra]]'' (1971) ([[44th Academy Awards|nominated for Academy Award]] for Best Original Score (Dramatic))\n* ''[[Lady Caroline Lamb (film)|Lady Caroline Lamb]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Voices (1973 film)|Voices]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Murder on the Orient Express (1974 film)|Murder on the Orient Express]]'' (1974) ([[47th Academy Awards|nominated for Academy Award]] for Best Original Dramatic Score)\n* ''[[Permission to Kill]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Sherlock Holmes in New York]]'' (1976) (TV)\n* ''[[The Accuser (film)|The Accuser]]'' aka L'Impr\u00e9cateur (1977)\n* ''[[Equus (film)|Equus]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[The Brink's Job]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Yanks]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[The Return of the Soldier (film)|The Return of the Soldier]]'' (1982)\n* ''Knockback'' (1984) (TV)\n* ''[[The Ebony Tower]]'' (1984) (TV)\n* ''[[Murder with Mirrors]]'' (1985) (TV)\n* ''[[Tender is the Night#Film, TV or theatrical adaptations|Tender is the Night]]'' (1985) (TV mini-series)\n* ''[[Poor Little Rich Girl: The Barbara Hutton Story]]'' (1987) (TV)\n* ''[[The Charmer (TV series)|The Charmer]]'' (1987) (TV mini-series)\n* ''[[American Playhouse]]'' (1988) (TV, 1 episode)\n* ''[[The Attic: The Hiding of Anne Frank]]'' (1988) (TV)\n* ''[[Enchanted April (1991 film)|Enchanted April]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Four Weddings and a Funeral]]'' (1994)\n* ''Swann'' (1996)\n* ''[[The Tale of Sweeney Todd]]'' (1997) (TV)\n* ''[[Gormenghast (TV serial)|Gormenghast]]'' (2000) (TV mini-series)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Richard Rodney Bennett: The Complete Musician.'' (Authorised biography.) Anthony Meredith (with Paul Harris). Omnibus. {{ISBN|978-1-84938-545-9}}.\n* \"Composer Sir Richard Rodney Bennett dies aged 76.\" Charlotte Higgins, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/dec/25/composer-richard-rodney-bennett-dies ''The Guardian''], 25 December 2012.\n* \"Sir Richard Rodney Bennett.\" ([https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/9765852/Sir-Richard-Rodney-Bennett.html ''Daily Telegraph'' Obituary].) 25 December 2012.\n* \"Richard Rodney Bennett, British Composer, Dies at 76.\" By Zachary Wolfe, [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/31/arts/music/richard-rodney-bennett-british-composer-dies-at-76.html ''The New York Times''], December 30, 2012.\n* Timothy Reynish, \"British Wind Music\", paper presented to the 2005 CBDNA National Conference\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Britannica|61007|Sir Richard Rodney Bennett}}\n*[http://www.chesternovello.com/Default.aspx?TabId=2431&State_2905=2&composerId_2905=100 Biography and list of works, published by Novello & Company Ltd]\n* [http://www.universaledition.com/Richard-Rodney-Bennett/composers-and-works/composer/47 Richard Rodney Bennett] biography and works on the UE website\n*{{IMDb name|id=0005961|name=Richard Rodney Bennett}}\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p37367|label=Richard Rodney Bennett}}\n* [http://sounds.bl.uk/Oral-history/The-Listening-Project/021M-C1500X0224XX-0001V0 Conversation between Richard Rodney Bennett and Claire Martin] \u2013 British Library sound recording\n*[http://www.bruceduffie.com/bennett.html Interview with Richard Rodney Bennett] by Bruce Duffie, March 25, 1988\n*[http://www.epdlp.com/compbso.php?id=668 Richard Rodney Bennett] at ''Epdlp'' (Spanish)\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/e651914f#p00943zz Appearance on Desert Island Discs, 19 October 1997] \n* [http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp68832/sir-richard-rodney-bennett National Gallery entry on Richard Rodney Bennett]\n\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Original Music}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bennett, Richard Rodney}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:English opera composers]]\n[[Category:Male opera composers]]\n[[Category:British ballet composers]]\n[[Category:English film score composers]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:English jazz composers]]\n[[Category:Male jazz composers]]\n[[Category:English male composers]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Composers awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Light music composers]]\n[[Category:LGBT composers]]\n[[Category:Burials at Green-Wood Cemetery]]\n[[Category:People educated at Leighton Park School]]\n[[Category:People from Broadstairs]]\n[[Category:Pupils of Lennox Berkeley]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Kent]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix    = [[Sir]]\n| name                = Richard Rodney Bennett\n| honorific_suffix    = {{postnom|country=GBR|size=100|CBE}}\n| image               = Sir-Richard-Rodney-Bennett.jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| birth_name          = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1936|03|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Broadstairs|Broadstairs, Kent]], England\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2012|12|24|1936|03|29|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[New York City]], US\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Classical music]]|[[film music]]|[[jazz]]}}\n| occupation          = [[Composer]]\n| instrument          = [[Piano]]\n| years_active        = 1954\u20132012\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}}  -->\n\n| module              = \n| module2             = \n| module3             = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Richard Rodney Bennett''' {{postnom|country=GBR|CBE}} (29 March 1936{{spaced ndash}}24 December 2012) was an English [[composer]] of film, TV and [[classical music|concert music]], and also a jazz pianist. He was based in [[New York City]] from 1979 until his death there in 2012.<ref name=\"Woolfe\">Zachary Woolfe [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/31/arts/music/richard-rodney-bennett-british-composer-dies-at-76.html?_r=0 \"Richard Rodney Bennett, British Composer, Dies at 76\",] ''New York Times'', 30 December 2012</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\nBennett was born at [[Broadstairs]], [[Kent]], but was raised in Devon during [[World War II]].<ref name=\"Woolfe\"/> His mother, Joan Esther, n\u00e9e Spink (1901\u20131983)<ref>{{Citation|last=Venn|first=Edward|title=Bennett, Sir Richard Rodney (1936\u20132012), composer|date=2016-01-07|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-105846|work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/105846|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> was a pianist who had trained with [[Gustav Holst]] and sang in the first professional performance of ''[[The Planets]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/Writers-and-Production-Artists-Ba-Bo/Bennett-Sir-Richard-Rodney.html |title=Sir Richard Rodney Bennett \u2013 Writer \u2013 Films as Composer:, Publications |publisher=Filmreference.com |accessdate=2014-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/38/Richard-Rodney-Bennett.html |title=Richard Rodney Bennett Biography (1936\u2013) |publisher=Filmreference.com |date=1936-03-29 |accessdate=2014-05-15}}</ref> His father, Rodney Bennett, (1890\u20131948) was a children's book author, poet and lyricist, who worked with [[Roger Quilter]] on his theatre works and provided new words for some of the numbers in the ''[[Arnold Book of Old Songs]]''.\n\nBennett was a pupil at [[Leighton Park School]].<ref name=\"Sweeting\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/dec/26/sir-richard-rodney-bennett | title=Sir Richard Rodney Bennett obituary | work=The Guardian | author=[[Adam Sweeting]] | date=2012-12-26 | accessdate=2015-07-24}}</ref> He later studied at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] with [[Howard Ferguson (composer)|Howard Ferguson]], [[Lennox Berkeley]] and [[Cornelius Cardew]]. Ferguson regarded him as extraordinarily brilliant, having perhaps the greatest talent of any British composer in his generation, though lacking in a personal style. During this time, Bennett attended some of the [[Darmstadt]] summer courses in 1955, where he was exposed to [[serialism]]. He later spent two years in [[Paris]] as a student of the prominent serialist [[Pierre Boulez]] between 1957 and 1959.<ref>Robert Ponsonby [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/sir-richard-rodney-bennett-composer-whose-work-encompassed-serialism-tonality-and-popular-music-8431646.html \"Sir Richard Rodney Bennett: Composer whose work encompassed serialism, tonality and popular music\",] ''The Independent'', 26 December 2012</ref> He always used both his first names after finding another Richard Bennett active in music.\n\nBennett taught at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] between 1963 and 1965, at the [[Peabody Institute]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]], United States from 1970 to 1971, and was later International [[Chair]] of Composition at the Royal Academy of Music between 1994 and the year 2000. He was appointed a Commander of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in 1977, and was [[Knight Bachelor|knight]]ed in 1998.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/for_christmas/_new_year/new_year_honours/43509.stm | work=BBC News | title=Life Peers to Order of the Companion of Honour | date=31 December 1997}}</ref>\n\nBennett produced over 200 works for the concert hall, and 50 scores for film and television. He was also a writer and performer of [[jazz]] songs for 50 years. Immersed in the techniques of the European [[avant-garde]] via his contact with Boulez, Bennett subsequently developed his own dramato-abstract style. In his later years, he adopted an increasingly tonal idiom.\n\nBennett regularly performed as a jazz pianist, with such singers as [[Cleo Laine]], [[Marion Montgomery]] (until her death in 2002), [[Mary Cleere Haran]] (until her death in 2011), and more recently with [[Claire Martin (singer)|Claire Martin]],<ref name=\"Sweeting\"/> performing the [[Great American Songbook]]. Bennett and Martin performed at such venues as The Oak Room at the [[Algonquin Hotel]] in New York, and [[The Pheasantry]] and [[Ronnie Scott's Jazz Club]] in London.\n\nIn later years, in addition to his musical activities, Bennett became known as an artist working in the medium of collage.<ref name=\"Wroe\">{{cite web|author=Nicholas Wroe |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/jul/22/richard-rodney-bennett-life-music-film |title=A life in music: Richard Rodney Bennett &#124; Music |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=2014-05-15}}</ref> He exhibited these collages several times in England, including at the [http://www.holtfestival.org/ Holt Festival, Norfolk]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://holtfestival.org/2011/fine_art.html |title=Holt Festival 2011 &#124; Fine Art |publisher=Holtfestival.org |accessdate=2014-05-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922184428/http://holtfestival.org/2011/fine_art.html |archivedate=22 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> in 2011, and at the Swaledale Festival, Yorkshire, in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swaledale-festival.org.uk/exhib |title=music, poetry, visual arts, walks, exhibitions, workshops |publisher=Swaledale Festival |accessdate=2014-05-15}}</ref> The first ever exhibition of his collages was in London in 2010, at the South Kensington and Chelsea Mental Health Centre, curated by the Nightingale Project, a charity that takes music and art into hospitals. Bennett was a patron of this charity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nightingaleproject.org |title=The Nightingale Project |publisher=The Nightingale Project |accessdate=2014-05-15}}</ref> Bennett is honoured with four photographic portraits in the collection of the [[National Portrait Gallery, London]].\n\nAnthony Meredith's biography of Bennett was published in November 2010.<ref>{{cite book | title=Richard Rodney Bennett: The Complete Musician | last=Meredith | first=Anthony |author2=Harris, Paul | isbn=978-1-84938-545-9 | publisher=Omnibus | year=2010 | url=http://www.omnibuspress.com/Product.aspx?ProductId=710841}}</ref> Bennett is survived by his sister Meg (born 1930), the poet [[M. R. Peacocke]], with whom he collaborated on a number of vocal works.\n\nBennett's cremated remains are buried at [[Green-wood Cemetery]], [[Brooklyn]].<ref>[https://www.green-wood.com/2013/sir-richard-rodney-bennett-dead-at-76/ Green-Wood]</ref>\n\n==Music==\nDespite his early studies in [[Modernism (music)|modernist]] techniques, Bennett's tastes were catholic. He wrote in a wide range of styles, including [[jazz]], for which he had a particular fondness. Early on, he began to write music for feature films. He said that it was as if the different styles of music that he was writing went on 'in different rooms, albeit in the same house'.<ref name=\"Wroe\"/> Later in his career the different aspects all became equally celebrated&nbsp;\u2013 for example in his 75th birthday year (2011), there were numerous concerts featuring all the different strands of his work. At the BBC Proms for example his ''Murder on the Orient Express Suite'' was performed in a concert of film music, and in the same season his ''Dream Dancing'' and ''[[Jazz Calendar]]'' were also featured. Also at the [[Wigmore Hall]], London, on 23 March 2011 (a few days before Bennett's 75th birthday), a double concert took place in which his [[Claude Debussy|Debussy]]-inspired piece ''Sonata After Syrinx'' was performed in the first concert, and in the Late Night Jazz Event which followed, Bennett and Claire Martin performed his arrangements of the Great American Songbook (Cole Porter, George Gershwin, Rodgers and Hart and so on). See also [https://www.theguardian.com/music/tomserviceblog/2012/jul/02/richard-rodney-bennett-contemporary-music-guide Tom Service's appreciation of Bennett's music] published in The Guardian in July 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/tomserviceblog/2012/jul/02/richard-rodney-bennett-contemporary-music-guide | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Tom | last=Service | title=A guide to Richard Rodney Bennett's music | date=2 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Film and television scores==\nHe wrote music for films and television; among his scores were the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' story ''[[The Aztecs (Doctor Who)|The Aztecs]]'' (1964) for television, and the feature films ''[[Billion Dollar Brain]]'' (1967), ''[[Lady Caroline Lamb (film)|Lady Caroline Lamb]]'' (1972) and ''[[Equus (film)|Equus]]'' (1977). His scores for ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]]'' (1967), ''[[Nicholas and Alexandra]]'' (1971), and ''[[Murder on the Orient Express (1974 film)|Murder on the Orient Express]]'' (1974), each earned him [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominations, with ''Murder on the Orient Express'' gaining a [[BAFTA]] award. Later works include ''[[Enchanted April (1992 film)|Enchanted April]]'' (1992), ''[[Four Weddings and a Funeral]]'' (1994), and ''[[The Tale of Sweeney Todd]]'' (1998). He was also a prolific composer of orchestral works, piano solos, choral works and operas. Despite this eclecticism, Bennett's music rarely involved stylistic crossover.\n\n==Selected works==\n\n===Instrumental works===\n*''Sonata'' for piano (1954, first published work)\n*''Impromptus'' (for guitar) (1968)\n*''Concerto for alto saxophone''\n*''Scena II'' (for solo cello; commissioned by the Music Department of the University College of North Wales, Bangor, with funds from Welsh Arts Council, first performed by Judith Mitchell 25 April 1974\n*''Concerto for Stan Getz'' (tenor saxophone, timpani & strings)\n*''Dream Sequence'' for cello and piano&nbsp;\u2013 first performed in December 1994 at the [[Wigmore Hall]], London by [[Julian Lloyd Webber]] and [[John Lenehan]]\n*''Elegy for Davis''\n*''Harpsichord Concerto'' (1980). Premiere conducted by [[Leonard Slatkin]]. St. Louis Symphony Orchestra. Richard Rodney Bennett, harpsichord.  \n*''Fanfare'' for brass quintet (2012)\n*''Farnham Festival Overture'' (1964) for orchestra\n*''The Four Seasons'' (1991) for Symphonic Wind Ensemble\n*''A Little Suite'', based on selections from Rodney Bennett's song cycles ''The Insect World'' and ''The Aviary''.\n*''Morning Music'' for wind band\n* ''Music for Strings''\n*''Party Piece'' for orchestra\n*''Reflections on a Sixteenth Century Tune'' for string orchestra or double wind quintet (1999)\n*''Sonata for solo guitar'' (1983)\n*''Sonatina'' for solo clarinet\n*''Summer Music'' for flute and piano\n*''Symphony No. 1'' (1965)\n*''Symphony No. 2'' (1968). Commissioned by the [[New York Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n*''Symphony No. 3'' (1987)\n*''Marimba Concerto'' (1988)\n*''Percussion Concerto'' (1990). Commissioned by and first performed at [[St Magnus Festival]], Orkney, soloist Dame [[Evelyn Glennie]], 1990\n*''Trumpet Concerto'' for trumpet and wind orchestra\n*''Partridge Pie'' based on The Twelve Days of Christmas\n*''After Syrinx I'' for oboe and piano\n*''Lilliburlero'' ''Variations for 2 pianos'' (2008) commissioned by the Dranoff 2 Piano Foundation in Miami\n\n===Operas===\n*''[[The Ledge (opera)|The Ledge]]'' (libretto by Adrian Mitchell) \u2013 1961\n*''[[The Midnight Thief]]'' (libretto by [[Ian Serraillier]])&nbsp;\u2013 1964\n*''[[The Mines of Sulphur]]'' (libretto by [[Beverley Cross]]) \u2013 1965\n*''[[A Penny for a Song]]'' \u2013 1967\n*''[[All the King's Men (opera)|All the King's Men]]'' (libretto by Beverley Cross) \u2013 1968\n*''[[Victory (opera)|Victory]]'' (libretto by Beverley Cross) \u2013 1970\n\n===Ballet===\n*''[[Jazz Calendar]]'' \u2013 1968\n*''[[Isadora (ballet)|Isadora]]'' \u2013 1981\n\n===Choral and vocal works===\n* A Good-Night \u2013 1999\n*''Missa Brevis'' \u2013 1990\n*''Sea Change'' \u2013 1983\n*''Spells'', written for soprano [[Jane Manning]]\n*''Five Carols: There is No Rose, Out of Your Sleep, That Younge Child, Sweet was the Song, Susanni'' Written for St Matthew's Church Northampton - 1967\n*''On Christmas Day to My Heart'', written in 1998 for the [[Nine Lessons and Carols|Festival of Nine Lessons and Carols]] at [[King's College Chapel, Cambridge]] in 1999.\n*''The Garden \u2013 A Serenade to Glimmerglass'', commissioned by Nicholas Russell for [[Glimmerglass Opera]] in honour of Stewart Robertson for its Young American Artists Program \u2013 2006\n* The Birds Lament\n* \"Tom o' Bedlam's Song\" (voice and cello){{snd}}1961 <ref>{{Allmusic |class=composition |id=tom-obedlams-song-for-voice-cello-mc0002687471 |label=Richard Rodney Bennett: Tom O'Bedlam's Song, for voice & cello |accessdate=7 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Albums===\nSolo:\n*2007 \"Richard Rodney Bennett: Words And Music\" (Chandos)\n*2002 Take Love Easy (Audiophile)\n*1995 A Different Side of Sondheim (DRG)\n*1994 Harold Arlen's Songs (Audiophile)\n*1992 \"I Never Went Away\" (Delos)\nwith [[Marion Montgomery]]\n*1977 ''Surprise Surprise''\n*1978 ''Town and Country''\n*1984 ''[[Puttin' On the Ritz]]''\nwith Carol Sloane (singer)\n*1988 ''[[Lush Life (Richard Rodney Bennett album)|Lush Life]]''\n*1989 ''Love You Madly'' (Contemporary)\nwith Chris Connor (singer)\n*1991 ''Classic'' (Contemporary)\n*1991 ''New Again'' (Contemporary)\n\nwith Mary Cleere Haran (singer)\n*1995 ''This Funny World: Mary Cleere Haran Sings Lyrics By Hart'' (Var\u00e8se Sarabande)\n*1998 ''Pennies From Heaven: Movie Songs From The Depression Era'' (Angel Records) \n*1999 ''The Memory Of All That: Gershwin On Broadway and In Hollywood'' (2011 reissue)\n*2002 ''Crazy Rhythm: Manhattan in the 20s'' (Var\u00e8se Sarabande)\nwith [[Claire Martin (singer)|Claire Martin]]\n*2005 ''[[When Lights Are Low (Claire Martin and Richard Rodney Bennett album)|When Lights Are Low]]''\n*2010 ''[[Witchcraft (Claire Martin and Richard Rodney Bennett album)|Witchcraft]]''\n*2013 ''Say It Isn't So''\nOpera\n*2005 ''The Mines of Sulphur'' (Chandos)\nOrchestral\n*1968 Symphony No. 1 (with works by Bax and Berkeley) \u2013 [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]], [[Igor Buketoff]] (RCA)\n*1972 ''Jazz Calendar'' / Piano Concerto \u2013 [[Stephen Bishop-Kovacevich]], [[London Symphony Orchestra]], [[Alexander Gibson (conductor)|Alexander Gibson]] (Philips)\n*1979 ''Spells'' / ''Aubade'' \u2013 [[Jane Manning]], [[Philharmonia Orchestra]], [[David Willcocks]], [[David Atherton]] (Argo)\n*1995 ''Partita'' / ''Four Jazz Songs'' / ''Enchanted April Suite'' \u2013 [[Britten Sinfonia]], [[Nicholas Cleobury]], the composer, [[Neil Richardson (composer)|Neil Richardson]] (BBC)\n*1996 ''Diversions'' / Symphony No. 3 / Concerto for Violin and Orchestra \u2013 [[Monte Carlo Philharmonic Orchestra]], [[James DePreist]] (Koch)\n*2017 ''Bennett: Orchestral Works , Vol 1 (Celebration; Marimba Concerto; Symphony No. 3; Summer Music; Sinfonietta)'' - BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra, John Wilson (Chandos)\n*2018 ''Bennett: Orchestral Works , Vol 2 (Concerto for Stan Getz; Symphony No. 2; Serenade; Partita)'' - BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra, John Wilson (Chandos)\n*2019 ''Bennett: Orchestral Works, Vol 3 (Symphony No. 1; A History of the Th\u00e9 Dansant; Reflections on a 16th Century Tune; Zodiac)'' - BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra, John Wilson (Chandon)\nChoral\n*2013 ''Letters to Lindbergh'' (Signum UK)\n*2013 ''Sea Change: Choral Music of Richard Rodney Bennett'' \u2013 The [[Cambridge Singers]], the composer and [[John Rutter]] (Collegium Records)\n\n==Selected TV and filmography==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n* ''[[Pickup Alley]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Face in the Night]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[The Safecracker]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[Indiscreet (1958 film)|Indiscreet]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[The Man Inside (1958 film)|The Man Inside]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[The Man Who Could Cheat Death]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[The Angry Hills (film)|The Angry Hills]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[Blind Date (1959 film)|Chance Meeting]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[The Devil's Disciple (1959 film)|The Devil's Disciple]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[The Mark (1961 film)|The Mark]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[Only Two Can Play]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[Satan Never Sleeps]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[The Wrong Arm of the Law]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[Heavens Above!]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[Billy Liar (film)|Billy Liar]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[Hamlet at Elsinore]]'' (1964) (TV)\n* ''[[One Way Pendulum (film)|One Way Pendulum]]'' (1964)\n* ''[[The Wednesday Play]]'' (1964\u20131967) (TV, 3 episodes)\n* ''[[The Nanny (1965 film)|The Nanny]]'' (1965)\n* ''[[The Witches (1966 film)|The Witches]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]]'' (1967) ([[40th Academy Awards|nominated for Academy Award]] for Best Original Score)\n* ''[[Billion Dollar Brain]]'' (1967)\n* ''[[Secret Ceremony]]'' (1968)\n* ''[[The Buttercup Chain]]'' (1970)\n* ''[[Figures in a Landscape (film)|Figures in a Landscape]]'' (1970)\n{{col-3}}\n* ''[[Nicholas and Alexandra]]'' (1971) ([[44th Academy Awards|nominated for Academy Award]] for Best Original Score (Dramatic))\n* ''[[Lady Caroline Lamb (film)|Lady Caroline Lamb]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Voices (1973 film)|Voices]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Murder on the Orient Express (1974 film)|Murder on the Orient Express]]'' (1974) ([[47th Academy Awards|nominated for Academy Award]] for Best Original Dramatic Score)\n* ''[[Permission to Kill]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Sherlock Holmes in New York]]'' (1976) (TV)\n* ''[[The Accuser (film)|The Accuser]]'' aka L'Impr\u00e9cateur (1977)\n* ''[[Equus (film)|Equus]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[The Brink's Job]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Yanks]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[The Return of the Soldier (film)|The Return of the Soldier]]'' (1982)\n* ''Knockback'' (1984) (TV)\n* ''[[The Ebony Tower]]'' (1984) (TV)\n* ''[[Murder with Mirrors]]'' (1985) (TV)\n* ''[[Tender is the Night#Film, TV or theatrical adaptations|Tender is the Night]]'' (1985) (TV mini-series)\n* ''[[Poor Little Rich Girl: The Barbara Hutton Story]]'' (1987) (TV)\n* ''[[The Charmer (TV series)|The Charmer]]'' (1987) (TV mini-series)\n* ''[[American Playhouse]]'' (1988) (TV, 1 episode)\n* ''[[The Attic: The Hiding of Anne Frank]]'' (1988) (TV)\n* ''[[Enchanted April (1991 film)|Enchanted April]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Four Weddings and a Funeral]]'' (1994)\n* ''Swann'' (1996)\n* ''[[The Tale of Sweeney Todd]]'' (1997) (TV)\n* ''[[Gormenghast (TV serial)|Gormenghast]]'' (2000) (TV mini-series)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Richard Rodney Bennett: The Complete Musician.'' (Authorised biography.) Anthony Meredith (with Paul Harris). Omnibus. {{ISBN|978-1-84938-545-9}}.\n* \"Composer Sir Richard Rodney Bennett dies aged 76.\" Charlotte Higgins, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/dec/25/composer-richard-rodney-bennett-dies ''The Guardian''], 25 December 2012.\n* \"Sir Richard Rodney Bennett.\" ([https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/9765852/Sir-Richard-Rodney-Bennett.html ''Daily Telegraph'' Obituary].) 25 December 2012.\n* \"Richard Rodney Bennett, British Composer, Dies at 76.\" By Zachary Wolfe, [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/31/arts/music/richard-rodney-bennett-british-composer-dies-at-76.html ''The New York Times''], December 30, 2012.\n* Timothy Reynish, \"British Wind Music\", paper presented to the 2005 CBDNA National Conference\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Britannica|61007|Sir Richard Rodney Bennett}}\n*[http://www.chesternovello.com/Default.aspx?TabId=2431&State_2905=2&composerId_2905=100 Biography and list of works, published by Novello & Company Ltd]\n* [http://www.universaledition.com/Richard-Rodney-Bennett/composers-and-works/composer/47 Richard Rodney Bennett] biography and works on the UE website\n*{{IMDb name|id=0005961|name=Richard Rodney Bennett}}\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p37367|label=Richard Rodney Bennett}}\n* [http://sounds.bl.uk/Oral-history/The-Listening-Project/021M-C1500X0224XX-0001V0 Conversation between Richard Rodney Bennett and Claire Martin] \u2013 British Library sound recording\n*[http://www.bruceduffie.com/bennett.html Interview with Richard Rodney Bennett] by Bruce Duffie, March 25, 1988\n*[http://www.epdlp.com/compbso.php?id=668 Richard Rodney Bennett] at ''Epdlp'' (Spanish)\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/e651914f#p00943zz Appearance on Desert Island Discs, 19 October 1997] \n* [http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp68832/sir-richard-rodney-bennett National Gallery entry on Richard Rodney Bennett]\n\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Original Music}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bennett, Richard Rodney}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:English opera 